'''Ōtorii Ōji''' is one of the {{ill|Kujūku Ōji|fr|Kujūku Ōji|ja|九十九王子|1=Kujūku Ōji|2=ja|3=九十九王子|4=fr|5=Kujūkuōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|lt=99 ōji Shrines|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kujūku Ōji|13=User:Immanuelle/Kujūku Ōji|qq=}} on the [[Kumano Kodō]].
==Overview== {{Shrine | Name = {{ill|Ōtorii Ōji|ja|大鳥居王子|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōtorii Ōji|qq=}} | image = | location = {{ill|Nishi-ku, Sakai|ja|堺市西区|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishi-ku, Sakai|qq=}}, {{ill|Sakai, Osaka|ja|堺市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sakai, Osaka|qq=}}, {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|ja|大阪府|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Osaka Prefecture|qq=}}, Japan | coordinates = | deity = | Affiliation = {{ill|Kumano Kōdō|ja|熊野古道|1=Kumano Kodō|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Kōdō|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Kodō|qq=}} - {{ill|Kumano Pilgrimage|ja|熊野信仰|1=Kumano shrine|lt=Kumano Three Shrines|lt=Kumano faith|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Pilgrimage|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Three Shrines|qq=}} | Established = {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamakura period|qq=}} (around 1201) | Map = }}
'''{{ill|Ōtorii Ōji|ja|大鳥居王子|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōtorii Ōji|qq=}}''' (おおとりいおうじ), also known as '''{{ill|Ōtori Ōji|ja|大鳥王子|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōtori Ōji|qq=}}''', was the 8th of the {{ill|Kumano Ōji|ja|九十九王子|1=Kujūku Ōji|2=ja|3=九十九王子|4=fr|5=Kujūkuōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Ōji|13=User:Immanuelle/Kujūku Ōji|qq=}} shrines along the historic {{ill|Kumano Kōdō|ja|熊野古道|1=Kumano Kodō|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Kōdō|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Kodō|qq=}} pilgrimage route, counting from the starting point at {{ill|Kubotsu Ōji|ja|窪津王子|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kubotsu Ōji|qq=}}.
== History == The existence of Ōtorii Ōji is documented in the 1201 ({{ill|Kennin era|ja|建仁|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kennin era|qq=}} 1) record of Emperor {{ill|Go-Toba|ja|後鳥羽天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Go-Toba|qq=}}'s pilgrimage to Kumano, titled *{{ill|Go-Toba-in Kumano Gyokō-ki|ja|後鳥羽院熊野御幸記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Go-Toba-in Kumano Gyokō-ki|qq=}}*, where it is referred to as "Ōtorii Shin Ōji" (大鳥居新王子). This suggests that the shrine was established relatively close to that period.
The name "Ōtorii" (meaning "Great Torii Gate") is believed to originate from its association with the nearby {{ill|Ōtori Shrine|ja|大鳥大社|1=Ōtori taisha|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōtori Shrine|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōtori taisha|qq=}} and its prominent torii gate.
== location == Ōtorii Ōji was located in the historical {{ill|Ōtori District, Izumi|ja|大鳥郡|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōtori District, Izumi|qq=}}'s Kita-Ōji Village, believed to correspond to the current area around the {{ill|NTT Ōtori Office|ja|NTT鳳営業所|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/NTT Ōtori Office|qq=}} in {{ill|Ōtori Higashi-chō|ja|鳳東町|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōtori Higashi-chō|qq=}} 7-chōme, {{ill|Nishi-ku, Sakai|ja|堺市西区|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishi-ku, Sakai|qq=}}.
It is also associated with the {{ill|Ōtori Minabehi Shrine|ja|大鳥美波比神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōtori Minabehi Shrine|qq=}}, which was relocated in 1879 ({{ill|Meiji era|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji era|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji era|qq=}} 12) to the grounds of Ōtori Shrine.
== Access == * '''{{ill|Ōtori Station|ja|鳳駅|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōtori Station|qq=}}''' on the {{ill|Hanwa Line|ja|阪和線|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hanwa Line|qq=}} operated by {{ill|JR West|ja|西日本旅客鉄道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/JR West|qq=}}.
